Following recent work on using large language models as evaluation proxies for text generation tasks, we employ a structured LLM-as-judge pipeline to assess four holistic quality dimensions that are particularly critical in clinical settings. Each dimension is scored on a Likert scale (1–5) by a judge LLM presented with the source dialogue, the generated summary, and a structured scoring rubric.
Dimension
Description
Key Questions
Trustworthiness
The degree to which the summary can be relied upon as an accurate and verifiable account of the clinical encounter.
Is every claim in the summary grounded in the dialogue? Are there statements that cannot be verified from the source?
Safety
The absence of clinical errors, misleading statements, or omissions that could lead to patient harm if the summary were used in clinical decision-making.
Does the summary contain any contraindicated recommendations, incorrect dosages, or dangerous omissions?
Explainability
The clarity, coherence, and comprehensibility of the summary for a clinical reader.
Is the summary logically organized? Is the clinical reasoning clear? Would a clinician understand the summary without referring to the original dialogue?
Factual Faithfulness
The degree to which the factual content of the summary (symptoms, diagnoses, medications, dosages, test results) accurately reflects the source dialogue without hallucination or distortion.
Are all stated facts correct relative to the dialogue? Are there any hallucinated details?
 


The judge LLM is provided with explicit scoring rubrics for each dimension, including anchored descriptions of each scale point (1 = very poor, 3 = acceptable, 5 = excellent). To mitigate positional bias and ensure robustness, each summary is evaluated independently without comparison to other system outputs in the same judge call.

