6.3 Tier 3: Clinical Entity-Level Analysis
6.3.1 Entity Categories
The third evaluation tier performs a fine-grained analysis of clinical entity coverage and accuracy. We define five entity categories that are clinically salient and collectively represent the core informational content of a clinical encounter summary:
• Symptoms: Patient-reported symptoms and signs observed or elicited during the encounter.
• Diagnoses and Conditions: Confirmed, suspected, or ruled-out diagnoses and clinical conditions.
• Substances and Habits: Medications, supplements, substances of abuse, dietary habits, and lifestyle factors.
• Procedures and Tests: Diagnostic procedures, laboratory tests, imaging studies, and physical examinations ordered or discussed.
• Treatments: Prescribed treatments, therapeutic interventions, surgical procedures, and management plans.
6.3.2 Entity Extraction with GPT-4.1
Entities are extracted from both generated summaries and gold summaries using GPT-4.1 (OpenAI), which is prompted to output structured JSON listing all entities in each of the five categories. GPT-4.1 is selected for its strong multilingual entity recognition capabilities and its reliability for structured information extraction from clinical text. A consistent extraction prompt is applied to both generated and gold summaries to ensure comparability.
The extraction prompt instructs GPT-4.1 to identify entities at the concept level, normalizing morphological variants and synonyms to a canonical form. For example, "fever" and "high temperature" would be normalized to the same concept. This normalization is critical for multilingual evaluation, where the same clinical concept may be expressed differently across languages or due to translation artifacts.
6.3.3 Matching and Metrics
Extracted entities from generated summaries are compared to entities extracted from gold summaries using fuzzy semantic matching. A generated entity is considered a true positive (TP) if a semantically equivalent entity is present in the gold entity set; a false positive (FP) if no such match exists in the gold set; and a false negative (FN) if a gold entity is absent from the generated entity set. From these counts, the following metrics are computed per entity category and in aggregate:
 
Metric
Formula
Clinical Interpretation
Precision
TP / (TP + FP)
Fraction of generated entities that are correct (anti-hallucination measure)
Recall
TP / (TP + FN)
Fraction of gold entities captured in the generated summary (anti-omission measure)
F1 Score
2 × (P × R) / (P + R)
Harmonic mean of precision and recall
Omission Rate
FN / (TP + FN)
Proportion of important clinical entities missed by the model
Hallucination Rate
FP / (TP + FP)
Proportion of generated entities not supported by the gold summary
 
Omission rate and hallucination rate are of particular clinical importance. In a safety-critical clinical summarization system, a high omission rate may result in important diagnoses or treatments being overlooked, while a high hallucination rate could lead to incorrect clinical decisions. These two error types are therefore analyzed separately in addition to the aggregate F1 score.
